# 14 May 2026

A recipe to run a local (free!) instance of gemma 4 + llama.cpp + aider on tuolumne.

1. Install aider.
    pip install --upgrade pip
    pip install pipx
    pipx install aider

2. Install llama.cpp
    git clone git@github.com:ggml-org/llama.cpp.git
    mkdir ./build
    cmake -S ./llama.cpp -B ./build -DAMDGPU_TARGETS=gfx942 -DGGML_VULKAN=off \
        -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release -DBUILD_SHARED_LIBS=ON -DLLAMA_BUILD_TESTS=OFF \
        -DGGML_HIP=ON -DGGML_OPENMP=OFF -DGGML_CUDA_FORCE_CUBLAS=OFF \
        -DGGML_HIP_ROCWMMA_FATTN=OFF -DLLAMA_CURL=OFF -DGGML_NATIVE=OFF -DGGML_STATIC=OFF
    cmake --build build --config Release -- -j 8

(Aniruddha suggests changing to -DGGML_HIP_ROCWMMA_FATTN=ON, then use --flash-attn on when loading the model.)

3. Create a sandbox directory.

4. In the directory above the sandbox, create a sandbox-config.yaml file.
    Here's an example (change the last two lines).

mounts:
    paths:
        # msr-safe work
        - "ro:/lib/modules"
        - "ro:/usr/src"
        # gemma models
        - "ro:/usr/workspace/lc-user/mapp/sandbox/models"
        # llama.cpp build
        - "ro:/p/vast1/rountree/machines/tuolumne/gemma/build/bin"
        # Aider
        - "ro:/g/g24/rountree/.local/share/pipx/venvs/aider-chat"

5. In the sandbox directory, create an environment file.  Change entries
    as needed.  An example:

# Needed for llama-server
export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/p/vast1/rountree/machines/tuolumne/gemma/build/bin:$LD_LIBRARY_PATH

# Needed for aider+gemma
export OPENAI_API_KEY="unused"

6. Grab a node on tuolumne.  --exclusive is required.
    flux resource list      # see what's available
    flux alloc --queue=pbatch --time-limit=4h --nodes=1 --exclusive

7. cd ./sandbox

8. source environment

9. Climb into the sandbox and pull the lid over you.

    /collab/usr/global/tools/sandbox/blackhole --config ../sandbox-config.yaml --device hsmp --device dri --device kfd

10. Load the model.  This will take some time.  Change to uses your llama-server.
    When you see "srv  update_slots: all slots are idle", it's done loading.

    /p/vast1/rountree/machines/tuolumne/gemma/build/bin/llama-server \
        --model /usr/workspace/lc-user/mapp/sandbox/models/gemma-4-31B-it-gguf/gemma-4-31B-it-BF16-00001-of-00002.gguf \
        --api-key "dummy" --alias "gemma4" -c 65532 -n 4096 --split-mode tensor > gemma.logs 2>&1 &

11. Using another terminal, clone a repo into the sandbox that you'd like gemma to work on.
    cd into that directory before running the next step.

12. Run aider Change to use your aider.

    /g/g24/rountree/.local/share/pipx/venvs/aider-chat/bin/aider --no-show-model-warnings \
        --openai-api-base http://localhost:8080/v1/messages --model openai/gemma

Notes:

People who build models don't have much incentive to make their agents work
well on local installations running somebody else's models.  So they don't.
I've not be able to get Claude Code or Gemini running locally.

Aider has a dreadful user interface, but it does work.
################################################################################
21-April-2026

This is provisional documentation.

1. Get an API key.
2. Put the API key into ~/.livai-api-key.txt
3. Create a sandbox directory and cd into it.
4. Create a sandbox-config.yaml file in your sandbox directory.
    Populate it as follows:

mounts:
    paths:
        - "ro:/lib/modules"
        - "ro:/usr/src"

(The last two lines are for compiling msr-safe.)
This needs to be in the directory from which you invoke the
claude sandbox script.  That's normally going to be inside
of a repo.  If you'd rather not add the file there, you can
specify its location as follows.

SANDBOX_FLAGS=--config=../sandbox-config.yaml /collab/usr/global/tools/sandbox/claude-sandbox

5. Create both a ~/.claude.json file and a ~/.claude directory
    with a settings.json file.  Both of these files should look
    like the text below.  Be sure to add your key.

{
  "env": {
    "CLAUDE_CODE_DISABLE_NONESSENTIAL_TRAFFIC": 1,
    "ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL": "https://livai-api.llnl.gov",
    "ANTHROPIC_AUTH_TOKEN": "PUT YOUR KEY HERE"
  },
  "model": "claude-sonnet-4.5"
}

6. Allocate a compute node.

7. Clone your repo of interest into the sandbox.

8. In the repo under the sandbox directory, run:
    /collab/usr/global/tools/sandbox/claude-sandbox
        or
    /collab/usr/global/tools/sandbox/codex-sandbox

9. To resume a Claude or Codex session, pass the --resume parameter
    to the *-sandbox command.  You'll need to be in the same directory
    as the one where the session was started.


View your API usage spend:
https://livai-tools.llnl.gov/usage/

